Title: Case-study in Knowledge Modelling with Benjamins' Library of Diagnosis Methods  
Author: Klas Orsvarn 
Date: March 14, 1995  
Address: Box 1263, 164 28 Kista, Sweden  
Affiliation: Swedish Institute of Computer Science Knowledge Technology and Methodology Group  
Abstract: A case-study in knowledge modelling using Richard Benjamins' library of problem solving methods for diagnosis tasks [3] is presented. The main result so far is an evaluation of the practical strenghts and limitations of this library, in supporting knowledge modelling in an example application, which gives a basis for extending the support provided by the library. But the main objective is to use the case-study for research on general principles for organ-ising libraries of task specific problem solving methods. The hypothesis is that weaknesses detected in the library can be regarded as violations of such general principles. This hypothesis is supported by suggesting some principles that could have prevented most of the detected weaknesses. Principles like that are needed, if we are to develop comprehensive libraries of task specific problem solving methods, since they cannot be evaluated by testing alone (i.e. by case-studies like this one).
