Reference-contexts: 1 Introduction This paper describes a case-study in knowledge modelling in the CommonKADS methodology <ref> [13] </ref> using Richard Benjamins' library of problem solving methods for diagnosis tasks [3, Ch. 5]. The main result so far is an evaluation of the practical strenghts and limitations of this library, in supporting knowledge modelling in an example application. <p> Suitability criteria may be static or dynamic. The latter refer to the knowledge roles in the current state of problem solving, and so can be used to achieve flexible problem solving, which is not possible in an interpretation model (it corresponds to strategic knowledge in CommonKADS <ref> [13] </ref>). But in the model generated in this case-study, this dynamic nature of suitability criteria is not needed. Benjamins makes no claims that his library provides the support for knowledge modelling that a knowledge engineer would need in practice.
